ve and to marry virgins and which teaches women to fear the men who court them. Taggart interprets the male-female dialogue voiced through storytelling by linking the content of specific tales to the life experiences and gender of the storyteller. Men and women, he finds, carry out an exchange of ideas by retelling the same stories and altering the plots and characters to express their respective views of courtship. This indirect narrative dialogue conveys an understanding of the opposite sex and establishes a common model of marriage that permits men and women to overcome their fear of each other and bond in heterosexual love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aCourtshipzSpainxFolklore. 0aSex rolezSpainxFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aAarne-Thompson tale type.  aAhigal.  aArroyomolinos.  aBarrado.  aBarry, Herbert III.  aBazagona.  aBecedas.  aCabal, Constantino.  aCabezuela.  aChrist.  aCortés Vázquez, Luis.  aCox, Marian Roalfe.  aDonjuanismo.  aDundes, Alan.  aFalassi, Alessandro.  aGarcía y Garcia, Segundo.  aGrimms, the (brothers).  aHerzfeld, Michael.  aJaraíz de la Vera.  aLewis, Oscar.  aLos Olivos.  aVirgin Mary.  aZipes, Jack.  aagrarian working class symbols.  aagrotowns.  abeauty: symbolism of.  abridal gift.  acannibals.  acarnival.  adance groups.  adefloration.  adisenchantment.  aeagle.  aenchantment.  aerotic aggression.  afamily structure.  afeminism.  afilial piety.  afolklore.  aforest.  agender segregation.  ahelpful characters.  aidealization of women.  aincest.  amale competition.  amass media.  amatrilocality.  amenstrual magic.  athieves.  augliness.  awitchcraft.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archi